   =20
      DAO governance
   =20
 =20
We have talked a lot recently about the mechanics of public-company mergers=
 and acquisitions. One feature of public M&A that is somewhat odd, when you=
 think about it in a certain light, is that mergers are subject to sharehol=
der vote. So in an all-cash acquisition (a big company buying a smaller one=
, a private equity leveraged buyout, Elon Musk buying Twitter Inc., whateve=
r), the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0Elon Musk or a private equity partner or the c=
hief executive officer of the acquiring company =E2=80=94=C2=A0will sign a =
merger agreement that legally binds the buyer to complete the deal (mostly!=
), while the seller =E2=80=94=C2=A0the chief executive officer of the targe=
t company =E2=80=94=C2=A0will sign a merger agreement that=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0legally bind the target company to complete the deal. In the merg=
er agreement, the target company generally agrees to something like =E2=80=
=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll ask our shareholders to approve this deal, and if they do =
then we=E2=80=99ll do it. But if they don=E2=80=99t, we won=E2=80=99t.=E2=
=80=9DMost of the time, the shareholders approve the deal, because most of =
the time the deal is at a premium to the current stock price and shareholde=
rs are pretty money-motivated. But this is not a law of nature or anything,=
 and if, for instance, the stock market and the target=E2=80=99s business g=
et a lot stronger in the months between the signing of the merger agreement=
 and the shareholder vote, the shareholders could say =E2=80=9Cnah we=E2=80=
=99re happier on our own=E2=80=9D and vote down the deal. Which they can ju=
st do. They=E2=80=99re not legally bound by the merger agreement; they can =
always second-guess what their agents =E2=80=94=C2=A0the board and the CEO =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0decided.Mergers work this way because it is a specific requi=
rement of corporate law; the relevant state corporate laws generally requir=
e a shareholder vote to complete a merger. There are a few other corporate =
decisions that require shareholder votes,=C2=A0but most don=E2=80=99t. You =
could imagine a world where every corporate decision =E2=80=94=C2=A0hiring =
a new employee, selling stock to a new investor, borrowing money from a ban=
k, signing a contract with a customer or supplier, changing the color of th=
e logo =E2=80=94=C2=A0was subject to a shareholder vote, but it would be a =
very=C2=A0unpleasant thing to imagine. How annoying that would be!Or you co=
uld imagine a slightly different world where the managers of the company co=
uld do all this stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0hiring and raising money and signing c=
ontracts =E2=80=94=C2=A0without consulting the shareholders, but the shareh=
olders always had a free option to reject the managers=E2=80=99 actions. Th=
e CEO hires a new chief technology officer, she signs a contract, she start=
s work, a shareholder says =E2=80=9Chey I don=E2=80=99t like this new CTO,=
=E2=80=9D the shareholder submits a shareholder proposal to reject her cont=
ract, the proposal passes at the annual meeting, and the CEO has to call th=
e CTO in and say =E2=80=9Clook, I know we signed a contract saying you=E2=
=80=99d be the CTO and get a $5 million equity award, but you have to under=
stand that that contract was contingent on shareholder approval, or at leas=
t on shareholder non-rejection, and the shareholders have rejected it for s=
omewhat whimsical reasons so now the contract isn=E2=80=99t binding.=E2=80=
=9D This seems like a chaotic and bad way to run a company.A DAO, or a dece=
ntralized autonomous organization, is like a corporation except that:=09Ins=
tead of having annual meetings with highly circumscribed ways for sharehold=
ers to submit non-binding proposals to management, the DAO has a continuous=
 Discord chat where shareholders can submit=C2=A0proposals anytime they wan=
t, and those proposals can concern core functions of how the company is run=
, and the shareholder vote on those proposals is at least kind of binding o=
n management.=09All the shareholders are really into crypto.And so one thin=
g that happens is that a DAO can enter into a contract, meaning that the ma=
nagers of its legal entity can sign a contract binding that legal entity to=
 do something, and then someone in the Discord chat can say =E2=80=9Cnah I =
don=E2=80=99t like that contract,=E2=80=9D and then the Discord chat can vo=
te to reject it, and then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0uh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I dunno? I think=
 under traditional legal principles, if the officers of a legal entity sign=
 a contract binding that legal entity to do something, a later vote by a Di=
scord chat to reject the contract doesn=E2=80=99t carry much weight. But I =
think a lot of people who are really into crypto would disagree.Here=E2=80=
=99s some DAO stuff:On May 20, Honey Barrel, whose online bio describes the=
m only as a =E2=80=9Cvanquisher of non-frens,=E2=80=9D woke up and chose ch=
aos. They=E2=80=99re a member of Merit Circle DAO, a decentralized autonomo=
us organization worth over $370 million that loans non-fungible tokens to p=
eople who play crypto games but can=E2=80=99t afford the buy-in, according =
to crypto research startup DeepDAO. In a 2,000-word post on the Merit Circl=
e DAO forum, Honey Barrel proclaimed that certain Merit Circle investors we=
ren=E2=80=99t pulling their weight.Their solution? Break the contract with =
the investor in question, Yield Guild Games, return its money, and show the=
 world that DAOs aren=E2=80=99t to be messed with. In the normal startup wo=
rld, one angry blog post would have gotten lost in the depths of tech Twitt=
er. But in the DAO world, where anyone who holds a token gets a say in the =
group=E2=80=99s future, the post lit a fire.The proposal from Honey Barrel=
=E2=80=94an average, albeit vocal member of the organization=E2=80=94threat=
ens to usher in a new, distinctly investor-unfriendly era in the DAO world.=
 Because if one DAO breaks its legal contract with an investor, what=E2=80=
=99s to stop others from doing the same? For venture capital firms that hav=
e put millions into DAOs=E2=80=94including giants such as Andreessen Horowi=
tz, Union Square Ventures, Sequoia Capital and Paradigm=E2=80=94the ripple =
effects could be existential.The proposal passed. The DAO voted to kick one=
 Merit Circle investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0Yield Guild Games =E2=80=94=C2=A0out =
of the DAO. YGG had bought its tokens from Merit Circle Ltd. (the legal ent=
ity connected to the DAO) for about $0.03 each; they were trading at about =
$1 at the time of the proposal. Merit Circle=E2=80=99s management team, who=
 presumably understood that =E2=80=9Crefund money to investors who aren=E2=
=80=99t pulling their weight=E2=80=9D isn=E2=80=99t really a thing, took th=
is proposal as obliging them =E2=80=9Cto renegotiate the terms of the finan=
cial agreements made between the DAO and Yield Guild Games=E2=80=9D; they n=
egotiated an agreement with YGG to buy them out at $0.32, a 10x return on t=
heir investment but still well below market value, and got the DAO to appro=
ve that. (Here is a useful Twitter thread from Tim Connors.) Merit Circle a=
nd YGG put out a rather peeved joint statement:The proposal singled out one=
 early stakeholder on the basis that it had not provided enough value in re=
lation to how many tokens it held. Merit Circle Ltd does not agree with thi=
s view. Yield Guild Games added value in many different ways although they =
were not often called upon to do so. They were also one of the first ones t=
o post their transparency & accountability thread to share and create a dia=
logue with the community.After taking in the proposal and observing the com=
munity=E2=80=99s feedback, Merit Circle Ltd reached out to Yield Guild Game=
s. Yield Guild Games worked with Merit Circle Ltd in the hopes of helping M=
erit Circle Ltd find a workable solution to appease their community whilst =
honoring the SAFT that Merit Circle Ltd had signed.We both recognized the a=
rbitrary nature of the MIP-13 proposal and the danger a precedent like this=
 could set for the Merit Circle DAO and the industry as a whole if agreemen=
ts are not upheld and investors are not respected. The chosen tool was too =
crude and did not do justice to prior agreements.The divergence between the=
 prior agreement and the DAOs proposal would have likely led to legal actio=
n against Merit Circle Ltd. While the legal question is one that could prob=
ably be argued at length, both parties agreed it was better to settle. This=
 would spare both parties from a costly, time-consuming, legal process with=
 uncertain outcomes. None of the parties had to settle, but both parties ch=
ose the constructive path to help Merit Circle move forward.Everything is l=
egal enough (because they settled), but still unnerving. Contracts with DAO=
s don=E2=80=99t entirely count, if the DAO can reject them. And DAOs don=E2=
=80=99t entirely count, if the managers can reject the vote of the DAO by s=
aying =E2=80=9Cwell we signed a contract.=E2=80=9DBy the way, one is tempte=
d to say, like, =E2=80=9Csmart contracts on the blockchain can solve this=
=E2=80=9D? Like in a world where the DAO irrevocably issues tokens to inves=
tors =E2=80=94=C2=A0or one where the DAO=C2=A0revocably=C2=A0issues the tok=
ens, with revocation explicitly contingent on a token-holder vote or on obj=
ective measures of performance or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0you don=E2=80=99t=
 have this ambiguity. But in a world where the DAO=E2=80=99s legal entity i=
s doing normal legal-entity stuff, but also vaguely beholden to the vote of=
 the DAO, you kind of get the worst of everything.
