<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">DAO governance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a lot recently about th=
e mechanics of public-company mergers and acquisitions. One feature of publ=
ic M&amp;A that is somewhat odd, when you think about it in a certain light=
, is that mergers are subject to shareholder vote. So in an all-cash acquis=
ition (a big company buying a smaller one, a private equity leveraged buyou=
t, Elon Musk buying Twitter Inc., whatever), the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0Elon =
Musk or a private equity partner or the chief executive officer of the acqu=
iring company =E2=80=94=C2=A0will sign a merger agreement that legally bind=
s the buyer to complete the deal (mostly!), while the seller =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the chief executive officer of the target company =E2=80=94=C2=A0will si=
gn a merger agreement that=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>legally bind =
the target company to complete the deal. In the merger agreement, the targe=
t company generally agrees to something like =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll ask our=
 shareholders to approve this deal, and if they do then we=E2=80=99ll do it=
. But if they don=E2=80=99t, we won=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Most of the time, the shareholders approve the deal, because m=
ost of the time the deal is at a premium to the current stock price and sha=
reholders are pretty money-motivated. But this is not a law of nature or an=
ything, and if, for instance, the stock market and the target=E2=80=99s bus=
iness get a lot stronger in the months between the signing of the merger ag=
reement and the shareholder vote, the shareholders could say =E2=80=9Cnah w=
e=E2=80=99re happier on our own=E2=80=9D and vote down the deal. Which they=
 can just do. They=E2=80=99re not legally bound by the merger agreement; th=
ey can always second-guess what their agents =E2=80=94=C2=A0the board and t=
he CEO =E2=80=94=C2=A0decided.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mergers work=
 this way because it is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/28141627.276598/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWxjb2RlLmRlbGF3YXJlLmdvdi90aXRsZTgvYzA=
wMS9zYzA5L2luZGV4Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5adc96f3" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">specifi=
c requirement of corporate law</a>; the relevant state corporate laws gener=
ally require a shareholder vote to complete a merger. There are a few other=
 corporate decisions that require shareholder votes,=C2=A0but most don=E2=
=80=99t. You could imagine a world where every corporate decision =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0hiring a new employee, selling stock to a new investor, borrowing mon=
ey from a bank, signing a contract with a customer or supplier, changing th=
e color of the logo =E2=80=94=C2=A0was subject to a shareholder vote, but i=
t would be a very=C2=A0unpleasant thing to imagine. How annoying that would=
 be!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or you could imagine a slightly differ=
ent world where the managers of the company could do all this stuff =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0hiring and raising money and signing contracts =E2=80=94=C2=A0with=
out consulting the shareholders, but the shareholders always had a free opt=
ion to reject the managers=E2=80=99 actions. The CEO hires a new chief tech=
nology officer, she signs a contract, she starts work, a shareholder says =
=E2=80=9Chey I don=E2=80=99t like this new CTO,=E2=80=9D the shareholder su=
bmits a shareholder proposal to reject her contract, the proposal passes at=
 the annual meeting, and the CEO has to call the CTO in and say =E2=80=9Clo=
ok, I know we signed a contract saying you=E2=80=99d be the CTO and get a $=
5 million equity award, but you have to understand that that contract was c=
ontingent on shareholder approval, or at least on shareholder non-rejection=
, and the shareholders have rejected it for somewhat whimsical reasons so n=
ow the contract isn=E2=80=99t binding.=E2=80=9D This seems like a chaotic a=
nd bad way to run a company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A DAO, or a de=
centralized autonomous organization, is like a corporation except that:</p>=
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Instead of having annual meetings wit=
